What Factors Contribute Towards World Happiness?¶

Contributors: Hanley Yin, Kyle Quain, Krris Vellayapan¶

Introduction¶

For our data, we used a dataset from Kaggle describing World Happiness.

The happiness scores and rankings use data from the Gallup World Poll. The scores are based on answers to the main life evaluation question asked in the poll. This question, known as the Cantril ladder, asks respondents to think of a ladder with the best possible life for them being a 10 and the worst possible life being a 0 and to rate their own current lives on that scale. The scores are from nationally representative samples for the years 2013-2016 and use the Gallup weights to make the estimates representative.

The columns following the happiness score estimate the extent to which each of six factors – economic production, social support, life expectancy, freedom, absence of corruption, and generosity – contribute to making life evaluations higher in each country than they are in Dystopia, a hypothetical country that has values equal to the world’s lowest national averages for each of the six factors. They have no impact on the total score reported for each country, but they do explain why some countries rank higher than others.

Dystopia is an imaginary country that has the world’s least-happy people. The purpose in establishing Dystopia is to have a benchmark against which all countries can be favorably compared (no country performs more poorly than Dystopia) in terms of each of the six key variables, thus allowing each sub-bar to be of positive width. The lowest scores observed for the six key variables, therefore, characterize Dystopia. Since life would be very unpleasant in a country with the world’s lowest incomes, lowest life expectancy, lowest generosity, most corruption, least freedom and least social support, it is referred to as “Dystopia,” in contrast to Utopia.

Data Collection and Data Cleaning¶

The dataset we used was actually comprised of 5 smaller datasets, which included data from 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, and 2019. A small nuisance arises from the fact that the columns are not standardized between all five years. As such, some minor data cleaning is necessary, which involved renaming some columns, dropping others, and converting column datatypes to the appropriate type. Other than that, we were able to nicely merge all five years worth of data into a singular dataframe without much headache.

Exploratory data analysis¶

First, lets take a brief look at some of the attributes, to get a better idea of their distributions. We do this by simply plotting some basic histograms of some relevant attributes, which include 'Happiness Score', 'Economy', 'Family', 'Life Expectancy', 'Freedom', 'Trust', 'Generosity', and 'Dystopia Residual', as well as computing the mean values of each.

As expected, much of the data was unimodal and appeared roughly normal. However, there were a few things of interest:

  • Trust was heavily skewed right, with relatively low values. This means that trust in the government did not play a very big role in the calculation of happiness
  • Conversely, Family was skewed left with a majority of the datapoints taking on high values, meaning that Family was an important factor in Happiness.

Lets see how much happiness changes per year, if it does at all:

In [13]:
plt.figure(figsize = (10, 6))
sns.violinplot(y='Happiness Score', x='Year', data=df, estimator='mean')
plt.title('Violin Plot of Happiness Score vs Year')
plt.show()

Over the course of these 5 years, it doesn't appear like global average of happiness score has changes much, which means it might not make sense to analyze how much happiness changes over time. (Or more realistically, we would need data on a much longer scale such as decades instead of years, as there is not much that can really be done in only five years to affect a statistically significant difference in happiness).

Lets see what statistics have to say about it: We will create a correlation matrix using Pearson Correlation Matrix, one which will display correlation as a continuous heatmap and one which bins correlations into discrete bins.

As expected, values highly correlated with Happiness Score were Economy, Family, and Life Expectancy, with other attributes taking on lower values.

Lets see how the data looks on a map: We'll have to average out the happiness scores for each country across all 5 years. To do this, we'll first group the data by Country, and take the mean of the remaining columns.

To actually plot data by country, we'll make use of the Geopandas Library. In particular, we'll join the "naturalearth_lowres" Geo-Dataframe with our merged dataframe on country code, which will allow us to plot the Happiness Score from our merged dataframe using the location column. In order to get country codes, we also used an external library country_converter to convert country names to the ISO-3 Standard country codes.

In [100]:
# Grouping all 5 rows from each country together into a single row by averaging out values
merged_df = df.groupby("Country").mean().reset_index()
# Generating country codes
merged_df['CODE']= coco.convert(names=merged_df['Country'], to='ISO3', not_found=None)

# Loading in the world GeoDataFrame
world = gpd.read_file(gpd.datasets.get_path("naturalearth_lowres"))
world.columns=['pop_est', 'continent', 'name', 'CODE', 'gdp_md_est', 'geometry']

# Doing a join on the two prior dataframes to get all necessary information into a singluar DataFrame
merge=pd.merge(world,merged_df, left_on = 'CODE', right_on = 'CODE', how = 'left')
merge.plot(column = 'Happiness Score', cmap = 'PRGn', figsize=(25, 10), legend = True)
Out[100]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f64a379e580>

This graph plots countries with around average happiness of around 5.379018 with gray colors, countries with below average happiness with increasingly intense purple values, and countries with above average happiness with increasingly intense green values.

Here, we can see that much of Eastern Asia and Southeastern Asia is pretty neutrally happy, whereas much of the America's and Europe are happier than the rest of the world. Most notably, most of Africa and Southern Asia appears in shades of purple, which may be also highly correlated to the developed vs. undeveloped regions of the world.
